{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c5370399-4364-4358-9732-4bf5c0743791","content":"This is a common issue. `AdjustResize` was deprecated in Android API 30+ and .NET MAUI's edge-to-edge support in .NET 10 means you need to use the **WindowInsets API** instead.\n\n## Recommended fix\n\nIn `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, apply an insets listener so the layout reacts to the IME (keyboard):\n\n```csharp\nusing Android.OS;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\n// inside MainActivity\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    // Let the app draw behind system bars / keyboard\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n\n    var content = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;\n    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new KeyboardInsetsListener());\n}\n\nprivate class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object,\n    IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n{\n    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(\n        Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n    {\n        var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n        var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n        // Use whichever is larger — keyboard or nav bar\n        int bottom = Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom);\n        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, bars.Top, v.PaddingRight, bottom);\n\n        return insets;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Why this works\n\n| Old approach (`AdjustResize`) | New approach (WindowInsets) |\n|---|---|\n| OS resizes the window | App observes `Ime()` insets and applies padding |\n| Deprecated API 30+ | Supported via AndroidX `WindowInsetsCompat` |\n| Conflicts with edge-to-edge | Designed for edge-to-edge |\n\n## XAML side — no special changes needed\n\nA standard chat layout works as-is:\n\n```xml\n<Grid RowDefinitions=\"*,Auto\">\n    <CollectionView Grid.Row=\"0\" ItemsSource=\"{Binding Messages}\" ... />\n    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row=\"1\" Padding=\"8\">\n        <Entry Placeholder=\"Message...\" HorizontalOptions=\"FillAndExpand\" />\n        <Button Text=\"Send\" />\n    </HorizontalStackLayout>\n</Grid>\n```\n\n## iOS\n\nOn iOS the keyboard avoidance generally works out of the box. If you still see overlap, add this in `Platforms/iOS/AppDelegate.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nUIKit.UIScrollView.Appearance.ContentInsetAdjustmentBehavior =\n    UIKit.UIScrollViewContentInsetAdjustmentBehavior.Always;\n```\n\nThe NuGet package `AndroidX.Core` (pulled in transitively by MAUI) provides `WindowCompat` and `ViewCompat` — no extra packages needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"75c3cbb1-7be4-419f-9bda-122252012c5e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue with keyboard handling in .NET 10. This is a known change — `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated/removed in Android 11+ and .NET MAUI has been evolving its approach. Let me provide guidance based on what I know.\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, you could use `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` on Android to make the layout resize when the keyboard appears. However, in Android 11+ (API 30+), `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` was deprecated in favor of the WindowInsets API (edge-to-edge).\n\n\nFor .NET 10, the recommended approach is to use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`, which automatically handles view scrolling when the keyboard appears, since the older `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` method is no longer viable on modern Android versions.\n\nFor a chat interface specifically, I'd wrap the content in a `ScrollView` so `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` can function properly, and on Android I'd configure the soft input mode through platform-specific APIs using `WindowInsetsCompat` rather than the deprecated `AdjustResize` setting. For .NET 10, the `WindowSoftInputMode` approach still works but requires combining it with proper edge-to-edge handling or using `WindowInsets` on newer Android APIs. The more reliable cross-platform solution is using a `Grid` layout with the input anchored at the bottom and listening for keyboard events to adjust padding dynamically, or leveraging MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` for automatic keyboard avoidance. Setting `SoftInput.AdjustResize` in `MainActivity.cs` is technically possible but deprecated on API 30+, so it's better to handle this through MAUI's platform-agnostic keyboard management features. Setting up the WindowInsets listener...\n\nActually, let me reconsider what's really needed here. The core issue is that .NET MAUI needs to handle keyboard visibility properly across platforms, and the most straightforward solution would be using platform-specific code on Android with the WindowInsets API, while iOS typically handles keyboard avoidance more naturally.","outputTokens":2301,"requestId":"143A:AAEEE:2FBD41:36B08C:6A03CF3C"},"id":"e7dcb415-a1e0-4dfe-a801-69d9fb67a42c","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:10:00.939Z","parentId":"b6591edf-fda0-4982-a3d8-b08090788d0d"}
